<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<FindBugsFilter xmlns="https://github.com/spotbugs/filter/3.0.0">
  <!--
    Reviewed suppressions (Chapter 16: suppress with a reason, never disable a whole detector).

    This module's subject is what each analysis technique detects, so it ships deliberate
    analyzer-target shapes, written to keep the module's own gate green while still showing the smell.
    Two of those targets are findings SpotBugs genuinely raises at this module's threshold — the bytecode
    data-flow leak (Move 3) and the type-misuse call (Move 2, which SpotBugs reaches by its own type
    resolution, the same conclusion Error Prone's CollectionIncompatibleType draws). Both findings ARE
    the teaching point, so the detectors stay fully enabled and each counter-example is named here,
    narrowly (by class, method, and pattern), with a reason and a pointer to the test that proves it. The
    remaining targets sit below the gate's chosen point and need no suppression (the empty catch carries a
    comment the house EmptyBlock check tolerates; the taint flow runs into an in-module sink base SpotBugs
    does not model as a JDBC injection).

    Note on the chapter's two suppression mechanisms: this FILTER FILE is the central, location-based
    control. The per-site @SuppressFBWarnings(value, justification) annotation is shown separately in
    SuppressionDemo (on a load-bearing EI_EXPOSE_REP finding) so the chapter's `justified-suppression`
    snippet displays the in-code form too.
  -->

  <!--
    Move 3 — data-flow leak. ResourceLeakDemo.readFirstLine opens a reader over a classpath resource and
    returns reader.readLine() without closing it on any path. SpotBugs finds it by data-flow over the
    compiled bytecode and raises OS_OPEN_STREAM ("may fail to close stream"); verified load-bearing (it
    fires when the detector reaches this method). The finding IS the Move-3 lesson, so it is named as an
    intentional teaching counter-example. Proven by
    StaticAnalysisDemoTest#leakDemoIsTheUnclosedResourceShapeAndTheFixReadsTheSameValue. The fix is the
    try-with-resources form in ResourceReader.readFirstLine, never this suppression.
  -->
  <Match>
    <Class name="org.acme.staticanalysis.ResourceLeakDemo"/>
    <Method name="readFirstLine"/>
    <Bug pattern="OS_OPEN_STREAM"/>
  </Match>

  <!--
    Move 2 — type misuse. TypeMisuseDemo.catalogueHas calls List<Long>.contains(int): the int boxes to
    Integer, which can never equal a Long element, so the call is always false. SpotBugs reaches this by
    type resolution and raises GC_UNRELATED_TYPES (verified High here, so the suppression is load-bearing,
    not decorative) — the same type-aware mistake the chapter attributes to Error Prone's
    CollectionIncompatibleType inside javac. The finding IS the Move-2 lesson, so it is named as an
    intentional teaching counter-example. Proven by
    StaticAnalysisDemoTest#typeMisuseQueryCanNeverMatchWhileTheTypedQueryDoes. The fix is the
    type-correct containsQuantity(List<Long>, long), never this suppression.
  -->
  <Match>
    <Class name="org.acme.staticanalysis.TypeMisuseDemo"/>
    <Method name="catalogueHas"/>
    <Bug pattern="GC_UNRELATED_TYPES"/>
  </Match>
</FindBugsFilter>
